nable construction solutions in the UK. Our business is made up of cement &amp; lime, aggregates, ready mix concrete</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">, asphalt and asphalt surfacing, maintenance services and waste services operations. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">As a UK based construction company our interest in domestically focused </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">investment in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">low carbon in</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">novation</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> is twofold; in the first instance we are continually looking </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">at ways of reducing the environmental impact of our own operations and have a strong track record in carbon emissions reductions</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">54</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">% since 1990)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">. Furthermore, as a forward thinking company one of our key objectives is providing solutions and products that</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> reduce the environmental impact of our </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">customers’</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> infrastructure, construction and other projects.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">Given the breadth of our own interest and the wider construction sectors position as an enabling industry our operations and / or services are likely to b</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">e relevant to most of the Technology Innovation Needs Assessments (TINA) that have been undertaken to date. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">In an attempt to focus our response</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> comments made in this submission are based on a review of the National Audit Office’s </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">(NAO) </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">report, the Industrial Sector TINA and the Domestic Buildings TINA. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">As suggested in the NAO’s report, the Government’s short term approach to funding is undermining the ability for the wider public funding programme to achieve the UK’s legally binding targets at the lowest cost possible. The most effective way of achieving</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> this would be by way of collaboration between Government, research institutions and industry. However, with funding only confirmed up to 2015 it reduces the ability of industry in particular, but also other potential collaborative organisations to secure </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">the long term funding that is required to undertake such projects. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">Confirmation of available UK support up to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">at least </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">2020 is therefore urgently needed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">Also,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">Government policies to date have concentrated on adding costs to energy in an attempt to drive</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> low carbon innovation. However, the cumulative burden of this cost, coupled with the absence of Government incentives and funding support for innovation in UK manufacturing</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> is making the UK less attractive for investment in general. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">here may be furthe</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">r opportunities to encourage / allow the market to innovate </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">without direct public funding by directing market incentives appropriately and improving the planning </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">and environmental permitting </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">system</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">, the refreshed TINA’s should seek to uncover such </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">opportu</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">nity </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">areas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">The Low Carbon Innovation Co-ordination Group’s (LCICG) work through the TINA’s appears to have been comprehensive. Unfortunately, there is a lack of awareness amongst industry about both the LCICG and the previous TINA’s that have been </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">completed. We therefore request that as part of the LCICG’s proposed collective strategy due to be launched in early 2014 that a much wider public awareness campaign is undertaken. Direct contacts should be made with leading organisations in the relevant s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">ubject areas, such as Lafarge Tarmac, and the associated trade organisations such as the Mineral Products Association</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> or the Zero Carbon Hub</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">Whilst we agree with the LCICG’s view that there are opportunities for some sectors to benefit from innovation f</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">ocused on another sector given the cross-sector applicability of some technologies, it should be noted that the specific requirements of some sectors may warrant a more specific focus. One example of this is Carbon Capture &amp; Storage (CCS) and the Cement Se</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">ctor. There are factors that are specific to the cement industry that mean that advances in CCS in the power sector may not be directly transferable. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:uppercase">T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">he balance between energy efficiency, renewable energy and other low carbon technologies will not be ri</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">ght until government provides the same balance of incentives and funding across all sectors of the economy</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:uppercase">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">The government needs to ensure that biomass direct heating is included in revisions to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">RHI</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none"> for the next spending review period</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:uppercase">.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none"> This will stimulate </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">innovation in industrial sectors, such as asphalt, cement and lime, which use direct heating in their processes. The success of this would be measured in the number of installations switching from fossil fuel use to biomass.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:uppercase">    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">At times the balance of fo</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">cus </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">of the public funding strategy </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">seems too quickly to revert to advanced technology solutions when there may be simpler forms of innovation available. For example, the Domestic Buildings TINA refers to improved fenestration, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">advanced insulation products </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">and low carbon cooling before / rather than looking at the performance of different fabric choices. Taking a fabric first approach is critical on individual projects to ensure that unnecessary additional services are not installed </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">and the same approach sho</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">uld be adopted for research into different innovative measures to ensure that resources are not be</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">ing </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">spent on solutions to problems that do not need to persist if different design choices </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">/ models </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">are adopted. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">Furthermore, influencing established design models to adopt a fabric first approach to energy efficiency by providing / investing in innovative ways of collecting in use performance data of buildings would enable carbon savings to be made in the period to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">2020 in the areas of pre-construction &amp; design and materials &amp; components which are currently shown as 0 in the TINA which </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">itself could be dissuading potential innovation investments from taking place. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">The Industrial Sector TINA refers to innovation o</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">pportunities around the development of low carbon cement in the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">UK; however, there is a reliance on such innovation being driven by a company called NOVACEM. It is our understanding that NOVACEM is no longer a UK based Company following it falling into ins</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">olvency last year. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">This unfortunate circumstance highlights the risks associated with relying on individual company driven single technology innovation. We would therefore suggest that the forthcoming LCICG strategy should drive more </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">investment</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> in low ca</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">rbon innovation via collaborative projects involving </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">established UK based companies. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">Certainly for the Domestic Buildings TINA we feel that </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">an effective stage to focus innovation investment is the area of increasing understanding / data regarding actual </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">building performance. Whilst this </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">is highlighted within the TINA</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> work undertaken to date, including by TSB, has focussed only on non-domestic buildings. However, a better understanding of the effectiveness of all innovations is critical to encourage a wid</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">er take up </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">by the market </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">and awareness of the need </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">for such measures </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">by the general public. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">I hope the above comments are of interest and go some way to informing the forthcoming inquiry. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">If you have any questions regarding the above, or would like to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">discuss any of the points raised in more detail, then please do not hesitate to contact me. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>